04724nam a22006735i 9780226348582DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263485827 a10.7208/97802263485822doi  a(DE-B1597)523242  a(OCoLC)951436868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPK2907.E7bG38 2017 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a891.20935382231 aGautam, Sanjay K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFoucault and the Kamasutra :bThe Courtesan, the Dandy, and the Birth of Ars Erotica as Theater in India /cSanjay K. Gautam. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Foucault and the Notion of Ars Erotica: Pleasure as Desubjectivation -- t2. Pleasure and Patriarchy: The Discourse of Dharma and the Figure of the Wife -- t3. The Courtesan and the Birth of Ars Erotica as Theater -- t4. The Courtesan and the Origins of the Nāṭyaśāstra: From Ars Erotica to Ars Theatrica -- t5. The Dandy-Guru and the Birth of the Discourses of Erotics and Theater -- t6. The City Dandy and the Vision of the City Based on Art -- t7. Foucault and the Kāmasūtra: Parting Ways -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Kamasutra is best known in the West for its scandalous celebration of unbridled sensuality. Yet, there is much, much more to it; embedded in the text is a vision of the city founded on art and aesthetic pleasure. In Foucault and the "Kamasutra", Sanjay K. Gautam lays out the nature and origin of this iconic Indian text and engages in the first serious reading of its relationship with Foucault. Gautam shows how closely intertwined the history of erotics in Indian culture is with the history of theater-aesthetics grounded in the discourse of love, and Foucault provides the framework for opening up an intellectual horizon of Indian thought. To do this, Gautam looks to the history of three inglorious characters in classical India: the courtesan and her two closest male companions-her patron, the dandy consort; and her teacher and advisor, the dandy guru. Foucault's distinction between erotic arts and the science of sexuality drives Gautam's exploration of the courtesan as a symbol of both sexual-erotic and aesthetic pleasure. In the end, by entwining together Foucault's works on the history of sexuality in the West and the classical Indian texts on eros, Gautam transforms our understanding of both, even as he opens up new ways of investigating erotics, aesthetics, gender relations, and subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAesthetics, Indic. 0aCourtesans in literature. 0aDandies in literature. 0aErotic literature, IndicxHistory and criticism. 0aErotic literature, Indic. 0aPleasurexPhilosophy. 0aSexxHistoryxIndia. 0aSexxPhilosophy. 0aSexzIndiaxHistory. 0aSex. 0aTheaterxInfluencexIndiaxCriticism, interpretation, etcxHistory. 0aTheaterxInfluence. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226348582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226348582.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Pac